      "content": "It is quite evident that the native population is incapable of self-governance, their inherent nature being marked by a lack of discipline, a propensity for violence, and a general disregard for authority. Theirs is a world of tribalism and clan loyalty, where the interests of the individual are subordinated to the whims of the group. In contrast, our own people are bred for civilization, with a strong sense of duty, a respect for authority, and a keen understanding of the importance of order and stability. The Indian, on the other hand, is a wild animal, untrained and unbridled, prone to outbursts of passion and irrational behavior. To entrust them with the governance of their own affairs would be to invite chaos and anarchy, and to undermine the very foundations of society. It is our duty, therefore, to guide them, to instruct them, and to impose our will upon them, that they may be civilized and brought up to the level of our own people. The notion that they might be capable of self-governance is a naive fantasy, a sentimental indulgence that ignores the fundamental differences between our two species.",
